    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-01-16T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-01-16T19:00:00-05:00" n="344"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d344">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/5251: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Chargé in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Munro</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-01-16T19:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 16, 1928—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>18. Your 23, January 13, 9 a.m. Department is unwilling to pass upon question of
                    Medrano’s eligibility under Nicaraguan constitution for election as vice
                    president. It cannot be placed in the position of approving even inferentially
                    the candidacy of any particular individual. Its interest consists in seeing that
                    a fair and free expression of the popular will is assured and beyond that it is
                    not prepared to go. Its statement as to Chamorro’s ineligibility<note n="12"
                        xml:id="d344fn12">See memorandum by the Assistant Secretary of State of a
                        conversation with General Emiliano Chamorro, October 22, 1927, <ref
                            target="frus1927v03#pg_367">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1927, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p. 367</ref>.</note> was addressed to a
                    special situation and by no means indicates that it will pass upon the
                    qualifications of candidates in general.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Olds</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
